snippet.textDisplay: I think people are going too far with this many worlds interpretation (hello Sean Carroll). At most, I think that the many worlds are restricted to the quantum level. Why should we pick just the superposition phenomena and apply it to the macroscopic world but not all the other quantum states/properties? Some of these should be observable through experiment. The sane way to think of this is that while any given particle could do the wacky quantum things, the probability of trillions of them (cat, human body etc) aligning to do the exact thing at the exact same time is very very close to 0. But sure, given enough time, my body could, at one point, teleport to Alpha Centauri.

snippet.textDisplay: None of this makes sense unless you solve the measurement problem. de Broigle Bohm theory solves that problem without the need for superposition. Entanglement and superposition are only mathematical tools, not a reality. "Measurement" is not special, any measurement is just another interaction. The many worlds interpretation is certainly better than the "copenhagen interpretation" (which is really a hodgepodge of individually incomplete interpretations), but it is a reducto ad absurdum of the concept of superposition. The probabilities of quantum mechanics are an artifact of our incomplete knowledge, not of some underlying probabalistic nature of reality.

snippet.textDisplay: I don't find it hard to believe that the universe divides at a quantum measurement. I do find if hard to say, definitively, that there's a branch in which Sean Carrol, or anyone for that matter, is president. Whether or not we're successful or unsuccessful in life depends on the decisions we make, not on the measurements of reality. The universe evolves according to the Schrödinger equation, these are the laws of physics. Consciousness, or agency, does not strictly evolve/unfold according to those laws, but evolves by predicting the outcomes of a certain thing happening in a probability distribution. The mind uses a model of reality based on a continuous stream of sensory data, the difference between the models predictions and the sample is known as free energy, or error correcting -- this is how agency evolves.

I do find if hard to say, definitively, that there's a branch in which Sean Carrol, or anyone for that matter, is president. Whether or not we're successful or unsuccessful in life depends on the decisions we make, not on the measurements of reality. The universe evolves according to the Schrödinger equation, these are the laws of physics. Consciousness, or agency, does not strictly evolve/unfold according to those laws, but evolves by predicting the outcomes of a certain thing happening in a probability distribution. The mind uses a model of reality based on a continuous stream of sensory data, the difference between the models predictions and the sample is known as free energy, or error correcting -- this is how agency evolves.

snippet.textDisplay:
Physicist here. This is pseudo-science. Check out walking droplets.

I believe that the many worlds hypothesis is pseudo-science. That isn't to say that other "universes" don't exist - there likely is more to existence than just our own observable universe, in my opinion - but only that 'many worlds', in which a new universe supposedly splits off every time a measurement is made, is nonsense. My research is in topological superconductivity, but another passion of mine is walking droplets, chaos theory and (general) pilot-wave theory. I admit I'm disappointed Veritasium could make a video like this after covering walking droplets some time back. The fact is that pilot-wave theory, in which a particle is "guided" by its pilot wave, is indistinguishable mathematically from standard quantum theory. Some decades ago, it might have been the 1960's or '70's, a person "proved" hidden-variable theories didn't work, only to be shown about a decade later that they'd made an assumption about so-called 'local reality' which doesn't apply to pilot-wave theory (or wave-based systems in general as I understand it).

Walking droplets exhibit many quantum effects, including single- and double-slit diffraction, tunneling through potential barriers, quantized orbits, Zeeman splitting, multi-modal statistics (think different eigenstates), even ferrormagnetic and anti-ferromagnetic ordering of spins. They have wavefunctions. I unfortunately don't have much time or energy these days to keep up with current research on them. They've recently discovered "superwalkers" though (with subharmonic vibration frequencies used for the fluid bath along with the main frequency) with yet more interesting behaviours. Bush from MIT does walking droplet research, among others.
